Density plots

library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

The K-mer analysis toolkit produces âdensity plotsâ. They are heatmaps that combine the GC content of k-mers with their frequency in the input file, which is a fasta file in this case. However, the plots made by kat are not easy to compare, because kat automatically sets the range of k-mer frequencies that are displayed, producing very different plots for different input files. Below, I assume that kat gcp counts k-mer occurrences between 0 and 1000, which I think is always the case.

for (i in 1:10) {
   input    <- sprintf('kat-gcp%02i.mx', i)
   gcp      <- read.table(input)
   gcp$GC   <- seq(0,26)
   gcp_long <- gather(gcp, key='multiplicity', value='frequency', 1:1001)
   gcp_long$multiplicity <- rep(seq(0:1000), each=27)
   head(gcp_long)
   assign(sprintf('p%02i', i), ggplot(data=gcp_long, mapping=aes(x=multiplicity, y=GC, fill=frequency)) +
      geom_tile() + scale_fill_gradientn(trans='log', colors=terrain.colors(10), breaks=c(1,100,10000,1e6), na.value='blue') +
      ggtitle(sprintf('Sample %02i', i)))
}

grid.arrange(p01, p02, p03, p04, p05, p06, p07, p08, p09, p10, nrow=5)

If these were single-genome samples, I would say the sequencing effort was not enough, because the frequency of k-mers drops abruptly, without the typical heap that would correspond to the average coverage of unique sequences. However, being a metagenomics sample, an alternative explanation is the very low diversity of the sample. If the bacterial community is dominated by a single species, over 50% of the sequencing effort may be used in sequencing that species at high covarge (long green tails), while the other 50% of the sequencing effort is thinly spread among all the low-frequency species (brown and white peak on the left). Of course the tall peak on the left of each pannel also includes the k-mers with sequencing errors.
